@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Main"

@{b}Introduction:@{ub}

Oh no, yet another @{"BootSelector" link "BootSelector" 0}?! Yes it`s yet another BootSelector.

This BootSelector wasn`t developed because there where no alternatives.
Infact I tried a various number of Boot-Tools and all were useful. So
this BootSelector whether integrates all advantages of other Boot-Tools
nor is perfect- but fits my needs best.

The most important features so far:

 o GUI to configure BootSelector
 o (De-)Install-button in MUIPrefsBS
 o black screen while booting
 o Installation in startup-sequence
 o ...

The most BootSelectors I know are either longwinded installed by editing
startup-sequence or splitting them and rename it into StartupI,II or IV 
(something chaotic), require knowledge not every user has (prefs-files
to be edited via Ced, Memacs,... or any other editor) or open a PAL-Screen
when booting which causes an ugly relay-sound when opening Workbench with
different screenmode.
So I developed MUIPrefsBS for my own but now I provide it for free to be
used by everyone and maybe you like and use it.
If you like this program please mail or write, maybe you have any sugges-
tion how to improve MUIPrefsBS.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Introduction"

@{b}Installation:@{ub}

Installation is done by the Installer.

When all files are installed you have to start MUIPrefsBS one time to
add the BootSelector-Call to startup-sequence. That is done by simply
pressing the @{"(De-)Install" link "MUIPrefs" 20} button.

That button also removes BootSelector-Call when it`s pressed a second
time.

@{u}Technical Info:@{uu}

   Files are copied by the installer:
   
    MUIPrefsBS   to SYS:Prefs
    BootSelector to SYS:c     
   
   The BootSelector-Call in startup-sequence:
     :
     :
   ;BootSelector Startup - Don't remove!
    FailAt 21
    BootSelector
    IF ERROR THEN
       ENDCLI
    ENDIF
   ;BootSelector End
     :
     :
   It`s inserted directly below comment-lines.

You have the choice to install files where you want but then (De-)In-
stall doesn`t work for install. For deinstall it will work if comment-
lines exist.

At least: Use the (De-)Install button, it`s the easiest way to install
BootSelector-call. (see @{"MUIPrefsBS" link "MUIPrefs" 0})
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "MUIPrefs"
@prev "Installation"

@{b}System Requirements:@{ub}

This little program needs at least:

 o AMIGA(tm) or something compatible
 o @{"MUI" link "MUI" 0} for BootSelector preferences-program
 o lowlevel.library for @{"BootSelector" link "BootSelector" 0} V.1.00

It won`t work on:

 o PC and something compatible (e.g. coffee maker)

@{i}Remarks:
1)  MUI is needed for preferences-program only, and it even needn`t be
    registered. 
@endnode

@node "MUIPrefs" "MUIPrefs"
@next "BootSelector"
@prev "Requirements"

@{b}MUIPrefsBS:@{ub}

MUIPrefsBS is the graphical user interface for BootSelector in typical
MUI-look.

@{b}Startup's:@{ub}
 o @{u}Startup`s:@{uu}
   Here you define which script is executed when pressing a mouse-button
   while booting. You can define 5 scripts which is the number of combi-
   nations possible when using a 3-button-mouse excluded LMB and RMB at
   the same time (then bootmenu is started)

 o @{u}Set Quit:@{uu}
   You can choose how to quit your script:

   1. If you don`t set quit your script is executed and when finished BS
      will continue to execute startup-sequence   

   2. If you set quit flag only your script is executed.

@{b}Global:@{ub}
 o @{u}Print errormessages (yes/no):@{uu}
   With this option you force BootSelector to report when an error occured.
   BootSelector always tries to execute normal startup-sequence at least
   and to "LoadWB". Screen stays dark if not selected and you maybe doesn`t
   realize that your script hasn`t executed.
   
 o @{u}DOS-Command:@{uu} 
   Possibility to define a DOS-command which is executed for every script.
   
@{b}Buttons:@{ub}
 o @{u}Save:@{uu}
   No words!

 o @{u}(De-)Install:@{uu}
   Does add or remove BootSelector-call in start-sequence. When removing 
   files are not deleted from disk, you have to delete them manual.

 o @{u}Cancel:@{uu}
   See below (save-button).
@endnode

@node "BootSelector" "BootSelector"
@next "Developer"
@prev "MUIPrefs"

@{b}BootSelector:@{ub}

The BootSelector itself, to be found in "C:"-Directory.

BootSelector provides the possibility to execute various scripts by
simply press a mousebutton when booting.

You can define which scripts shall be executed for different mouse-
buttons using @{"MUIPrefsBS" link "MUIPrefs" 0}

 @{b}Pay attention:  There are different versions of BootSelector and
                 every version has it`s own system requirements.@{ub}

 @{u}Version 1.00@{uu}
 o uses lowlevel-library to detect pressed mouse buttons.

 @{u}Version 1.10@{uu}
 o uses "input.device", but it`s still under construction.
   This version will run on every Amiga(tm).
@endnode

